What a doll!
Posed to sit on a rock and sing
some sailors to their doom.
A Siren is a monster from Greek mythology.
they are often depicted as sea creatures
that lured sailors to their deaths
with their songs.
My model is a fantasy rendering.
She has a aquatic appearance,
some of the features of a human female
but clearly not a beauty! Modeled in sculptris.
Truespace 5 used to cut the flat bottom.

I made the test print without infill and 2 shells.
I used no support, the arms are a challenge for some printers,
I use a replicator so the platform only moves down. For printers
that move the build platform, i think the arms might cause issues.
so in breif no support was needed on my machine, some might need support. I will do another print (in a day or so) using infill.
The test print has a few pinholes that might go away with infill.
As an alternative finish using a goop of ABS/acetone to fill in defects like the pinholes. (the attached pics are without any finishing).
I have had great success with using the "goop" to fix
separation cracks and top pinholes. I suggest a decent size print to get the full effect of the scales
and facial details that would get lost on a smaller print.
my stl has the size I printed it at. roughly 100mm (4 inches) I did another print using 10% infill. and larger.
It prints much nicer in the larger size.

description.text:

Here's a non-Kossel Clear specific version of this - http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:333167 And one for the Raspberry Pi 2, 3 or B+ - http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1771908 Frame mounted Raspberry Pi case for the Blue Eagle Labs Kossel Clear. The logo on the case is used with permission from Blue Eagle Labs. (http://www.blueeaglelabs.com/) A USB Wi-Fi adapter is at the end of an extension cable. It gives me better coverage than if the adapter is plugged directly in the Pi. I made a mount for the cable to keep the adapter in the air - http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:241023. A ball joint allows the camera angle to be adjusted. I used a 4" flex cable from Adafruit - http://www.adafruit.com/products/1646. It's a lot shorter than the original cable. There's a rectangular collar that can be installed around the socket arms to apply tension to the ball. You may not need it if the socket arms are printed with PLA. There's a gusset inside of the case that keeps the arms parallel, but ABS seems to be a bit flexible. I opted to add a collar as opposed to beefing up the arms. Why? I don't know. The mount keeps the camera close to the print bed -- too close in fact so the Pi's camera can't really focus on the print job. I might look into trying accessory lenses to bring the focus in. But otherwise, it does a good job of allowing me to monitor the print job via OctoPrint. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JVz2VNi9_BQ

Made these for Halloween. Based the design to look similar to the ones used in killer klowns from outer space These are hollow to allow for some maker magic.

UPDATE
if you print this in "glow-in-the-dark" material use some bright white LED or the ones that have a blue hint to them; affix these inside and they "Charge" the material when turned on so it glows super bright.
Simple circuit; speaker, Arduino Pro, 5v regulator and female dc to pair with battery pack Completed prints (V1.5.0)

Parts List
  • Arduino Pro (Keeping it small)
  • Lights for the front cups (9 WS2812B "NeoPixels")
  • Trigger is a NO push button (Size: approx. 24 x 19 x 19 mm)
  • Voltage regulator, this can get done multiple ways. I went with a L7805CV
  • 8-Ohm speaker (dont remember where I got this)
  • 18650 Battery Holder
  • (2)18650 Rechargeable Batteries

Circuit Diagram Caution

Depending on speaker type/size/power requirements; you may need a transistor or even a small amp to operate the speaker.

Arduino files:
v2.ino (Main script)
Pitches.h (segmented "defines" of tones; didn't want to see them in the main code)

Design Changes/Discrepancies
  1. I was not happy with the handle setup as seen in the pics, so the STL files have been changed so the handle affixes to the main body internally, this gives a nice look and makes the handle a single print vs 2.
  2. you cannot see the batteries in the pics; they are affixed to the lid.
  3. you dont need a DC plug as seen, It just my design process; I like the prop to be female plugs and the battery packs to be male plugs

title: White Wizard - Eachine Wizard Pod
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I never owned an Eachine Wizard but I really like the design of the frame (QAV-R clone ofcourse), except for the fact that those longer bodies are a bit on the heavy side, now a days.

On Banggood I found out that they sell the smaller sandwich/body plates, and the arms of the x220s, seperately. That, combined with 4x 25mm standoffs, some m3 bolts and my canopy design, makes quite a nice racing frame!

Shop for these parts to make it complete:

1x Base plate
1x Stretched-X arms
1x 25mm standoffs (4x in build)
1x M3 bolts (12x 10mm 4x 5mm)
1x M3 nuts (4x in build)
1x Anti Vibration standoffs
1x Runcam Micro Swift 2
1x Eachine VTX03
1x Frsky XM+
1x BFF3 clone
1x Tattoo 35a + BR2306s combo

Some things to keep in mind:

  • Buy the original x220 arms if you want a stronger quadcopter, those arms are wider
  • You can use one base plate to reduce weight but makes the construction weaker
  • Use 22-27cm long Lipo straps
  • Use longer standoffs to fit a stack of multiple PCB's
  • The pod fits micro sized cams only at 30 degrees minimum

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Infill:

+35%

Notes:

Choose an infill of at least 35% and a minimum of 2 walls for the pod. Otherwise some parts will be too thin (depending on the extrusion).

Of course you print the pod, lipo grip and strap plate with TPU.
Print the locknut bracket with a sturdier plastic. PLA with a minimum infill of 30% works fine.

Iâ€™ve got no clue about how sturdy MakerBot printed parts are, this means that I donâ€™t know if the parts I designed are thick enough to support the weight of the camera and steppers. Iâ€™m maybe plain wrong ! However, parts size have been carefully designed to fit into Makerbotâ€™s build envelope. The only overhangs are holes, therefore the parts should be printable on a MakerBot (At least, I hope !). STL parts have been checked with Netfabb and are manifold EDIT:I reuploaded the STL parts. They are now oriented in build direction This half automatic pano head has been designed to take pictures using a Canon Powershot A560 compact digital camera. The purpose is to shoot panoramas without getting into the risk of forgetting to take THE PICTURE absolutely needed to get a complete panorama (when you donâ€™t have got a wide angle lens, you need to take a lot of pictures!)... The head moves left/right and up/down. Two NEMA 17 sized stepper motors are controlled by an Arduino (or compatible clone) using two Sparkfun\'s Easydriver. The shutting mecanism will be controlled by Arduino. The Canon Powershotâ€™s normally donâ€™t have remote shutting capabilities. Fortunately, a great open source software package can add a lot of functionalities to these cameras: CHDK. It adds remote shutting by detecting when voltage is applied on camera usb port.
This head has to be mounted on a standard tripod.
Function: When pressing the start/stop button, the camera will take a picture (or more, if CHDK â€œbracketing in continuous modeâ€ is checked â€“ needed for HDR), then moves upward, takes a picture,â€¦ , then moves left,then moves downwards, takes a picture, â€¦ ,and it does the same column after column. When the necessary pictures have been taken, the photograph has to press the start/stop button. After, the reset button has to be pressed to put the pano head back in starting position (only horizontal axis needs to be moved). Advantages of this design:
-No need to carry a notebook to control this head.
-Simple to use. drawbacks of this design:
  • the row/column intervals and time between moves can only be changed by editing the arduino sketch.
    • No care taken about â€œNo-parallax pointâ€ for now.

description.text:
This is a modification of the Anet A8 printer frames to synchronize the 2 z-Axis motors. This is an update of the Anet A8 Z Redux - Synchronized motors by uanCarlos_3design http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2097301

I had ongoing z-axis syncing probelms between the left and right sides. Re-wiring the two z-axis motors in series helped but did not solve the problem. Finally I tried neoxM3's frames but my z-axis screws were too short.

My rework
Since the z-axis screws were too short to extend above the previous one piece frame plates, I split each plate into 2 components to lower the front half to allow the rods to extend high enough to connect the pulleys. Even with this I had to extend the rods further by pulling each out of the flex collar as far as possible, And pull the collars up from the motor shafts are far as possible. With this design the right motor is no longer needed but can left attached.

The pulleys on the left side are designed so the belt wraps around the geared pulley over 80%. The rear pulley sits in a slot in the frame so it can be adjusted to balance the belt's tension. I find the belt does not need to be very tight if both motors are attached.

After I took the photos I extended the slot under bearing "D." This gives more range for setting the belt tightness.

"A" 2 qty-8mm gt2 geared pulleys
"B,C,D" 6 qty-623ZZ 3x10x4mm Ball Bearings Shielded Radial Bearings.

Wanna build your own Lightsaber; cool. Here is the design I went with. its just a printed top cover and bottom cover for a PVC pipe.

This is not for the beginner maker; this has some fine soldering to do and restricted space; But its all worth it IMHO.

Design Proccess

So I had a list of goals for this to meet

  1. Had to light up
  2. Waned to to show a lite crystal (not shown in pictures, but its chamber is)
  3. Needs to have a removable blade (telescoping is just not an option for me)
  4. Needs presets/modes for different events (kept the emitter generic so it didn't look funny in different modes)
  5. Needs a safety switch to
    • Show what mode its in (dont want the mode always lite)
    • So if the encoder is bumped accidentally mode does not change

Simple list; and achieved

Things in the making
  • You dont see the blade in the pics?
    • its still in the making; I've tested the connection point it makes to ensure that it will light when connected, but now I'm testing out lengths and LED placement to get maximum glow. It'll be made with Polycarbonate Tubing there is a large amount of information out there where others have made lite blades with it. I'll follow the same process the only change will be the connection to the hilt.
  • Audio
    • this was not in my initial requirements (no idea why)
    • this will get updated once audio is added, there are just so many ideas
    • I think the future button will play some snippets when pressed
    • Also a motion switch that will play blade motion sounds when the blade is ignited and swinging

• 1" PVC (hilt body and length start with about 8"; you'll be trimming it down)
  • Arduino Pro (or similar, just keep it small to fit in the PVC pipe)
  • Rotary Encoder (Mode selector)
  • 1 NO switch (1 for future, 1 as a safety switch for mode change)
  • Voltage regulator, this can get done multiple ways. I went with a L7805CV
  • 6 WS2812B "NeoPixels" (1 for the crystal 5 for the blade)
  • 7-segment LED
  • 8-Bit Shift Register
  • 7 220 ohm reisitors (to protect the 7-seg LED)
  • 18650 Rechargeable Batteries
  • 18650 Battery Holder
  • 1/4" X 1/16" Discs magnets to attach blade
  • rocker switch for power control

Assembly and layout
  1. Get the Parts printing; it takes some time.
  2. Cut a channel down the PVC aprox 18mm wide and 63mm long (remember removing more later is easier then starting over from removing too much; set aside, we'll come back once the top is printed)
  3. Build the 7-Seg LED part of the diagram (IC, resitors and LED)
  4. Build the buttons and encoder part of the diagram
  5. Set to side as the rest we need to know the length of the handle to move forward
  6. Once the 2 parts are done printing, slid the top on to the PVC, aligning the channel with the crystal box as not to break it
  7. Mark Where the 7-seg, encoder, push-buttons and power switch go so you can cut them out later; you might have to file and trim the channel to get the top to fit; however dont go to large as we dont the channel to be seen
  8. Now grip the handle comfortably and mark the bottom of your grip, add about 25mm and trim the PVC (remember removing more later is easier then starting over from removing too much)
  9. Add the bottom section to the PVC (this section will hold the battery pack and regulator) repeat above step if handle is still too long
  10. Now remove the printed parts and trim out the marked areas for the power switch, encoder, etc.
  11. Dry fit the parts; if it all fits its now time for a paint job, remove the electronics and paint your saber; after painting I used foil tape in the crystal chamber to reflect the light around
  12. Drill a hole in the crystal chamber to allow light to penetrate; affixing the WS2812B inside aligned to the hole just made is tricky, but you can do it.
  13. Now you can measure wires to go from perspective places down the handle and out to connect to the AVR; I like to be able to pull my AVR out of the handle far enough so that I can connect to it and reprogram for more features/bug fixes
  14. Now with the parts installed and wires draped down the inside of the handle, connect them to the AVR, load regulator and battery into bottom of hilt
  15. Program AVR and have fun!

title: 40MM Fan & BLTouch Mount for FLSUN Cube

description.text:
Note This design assumes you have either an E3D V6 clone or a V6 w/ their stock coolers installed. Its designed to have a BLTouch installed on it too, but its not required. If you choose to not use the BLTouch, then leveling can be accomplished via the Z Limit switch and using the bed leveling screws.Note

I designed this to work with my stock E3D V6, which had its heatsink cooler installed on it already, and the standard 40mm fan that came with the printer. Just print it. Mount it. Screw it on. Good to go.

As some installation notes:

Put some longer screws thru the x carriage mounting holes and put some m3 nuts on the screws.

Mount the fan first with the assembly not mounted to the x carraige. The screws will go thru the fan into the holes. They should catch in the holes and tighten up, like mine.

If you do mount your BLTouch, do it before you mount the assembly to the x carriage. Mount it using M3 Screws and nuts. Screw heads should be on the bottom side of the mount, nuts on top.

Once all the installation is completed, mount it to the x carriage.

I tried installing my BLTouch, but it didnt work. Not to worry, I can get good results just using the stock z limit switch and the leveling screws.

Print quality will improve DRAMATICALLY once you install this.

FLSUN Cube

Resolution:

.2mm - .32mm

Notes:

Print slow and steady. 10 - 15mm/s should do the trick if you have no cooler.

Also, when you slice it, rotate it so the BLTouch mount is straight up.

description.text:
(Le français suit l'anglais)

The zoetrope is one of the earliest animation devices. Invented in 1834 by William George Horner, it was originally named the Daedalum or “wheel of the devil”. It was not very popular until around 1867, when it was rediscovered and patented by William F. Lincoln in the U.S., and Milton Bradley in England. It was Lincoln who gave it the name “zoetrope” or “wheel of life”.

Manufactured in London, England in the 19th century, the base of the zoetrope that you see here was built out of wood, while the drum was built out of metal, possibly tin. The drum was painted black on the outside and white on the inside. Zoetrope strips would be placed inside of the drum.

To find out more about this zoetrope, please visit:
https://ingeniumcanada.org/ingenium/collection-research/collection-item.php?id=1987.0280.001

Note: The original 3D scan of the artifact is named “Zoetrope-artifact.stl“. It is meant to be viewed in a virtual environment using computer software. You can try printing it off, though we cannot guarantee the quality. We have modified the model into a more useable form (“Zoetrope-modified-base.stl“ and “Zoetrope-modified-stand.stl“). For educational activities that this modified model can be used in, please visit:
https://ingeniumcanada.org/ingenium/museums/education/3D-zoetrope.php

Our terms of use can be found at: https://ingeniumcanada.org/ingenium/doc/content/cstmc/CSTMC%20terms%20of%20use%203D%20ENG.pdf

title: Bar Keepers Friend Top & Bottom
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
IMPORTANT NOTE: I joke about the whole "fire hazard" thing in this post, but there are two important facts: 1) My dad is a fire chief, and he'd have my ass if he thought I was joking about fire and 2) in the product's MSDS it clearly states: "Not a fire hazard. Use extinguishing media appropriate for surrounding fire." So if this product does, indeed, cause a fire, you're doing something wrong!

I love the product Bar Keepers Friend.

Even though I know there should be an apostrophe somewhere in that name, the product itself is perfect. It's based on oxalic acid which, of course, is acidic and corrosive. You probably don't want to breathe this stuff in, or keep it on your skin for prolonged periods. But it's great, fan-fricken-tastic, at cleaning up things that need an acid-clean, and a scrubby, abrasive clean. I use it all the time in my kitchen, so I buy the larger containers (21 oz) at Sam's Club.

The problem with larger containers of anything is that sometimes you don't use the whole container in a reasonable amount of time, especially in a home kitchen. If you only use this container (a great value, by the way!) once a week, it might take you a year or more to go through the product. This means a couple of things:

1) If you have it right next to your sink - the perfect place for it - you might get water on the counter below the container. The container bottom is made of metal (yay!), but the bottom is very thin, and the rest of the container is basically a cardboard tube. Yay for recycling, boo for longevity. If you let this container sit on an on-again off-again wet counter for a few months, it'll start to bleed a little. And, again, oxalic acid is a corrosive substance. So maybe you don't want it leeching out onto your counter. That sucks.

2) Having it next to the sink, there are probably going to be water droplets flying all over the place if you're a spastic dish cleaner like I am. I go to town on dishes, and sometimes things splash. It's a splash zone. It's a sink, in the kitchen. You're going to get wet. Sadly, the powdered form of Bar Keepers Friend won't stay a powder very long if you keep hitting it with water. Every time I buy one of these, first the top gets all crusty (ick), and then the bottom starts to fall out (boo). That's just a matter of time in the kitchen.

What can you do?

Well, you obviously guessed what you can do: you can 3D print this awesome top and bottom piece! The bottom Thing fits perfectly (snugly!) around the 73.5mm diameter container, while the top Thing fits loosely around the top, so you can easily remove it.

Eventually, I may make a snug-fitting top, that presses against the metal top, and gives you holes, that way you have a flat surface to wipe away if it starts to get crusty.

Now, I know what you're saying: "But you have no idea if oxalic acid interacts with PLA!" That's right. I don't. I honestly have no idea if I just put a fire hazard in my kitchen. If you think that there's a possibility that oxalic acid might interact poorly with PLA (or whatever magic filament you want to print this with), please read up on the two to make sure things are cool. They'll probably be cool. But still...if the fire chief comes by after a major house fire and blames my Thing and your container of Bar Keepers Friend as the source of ignition, do not sue me! Live and learn, and please, post a comment featuring the lesson you learned, along with an I Made One, featuring the ruins of your life caused by my Thing. I promise everyone will be supportive to your face, and will wait until later to laugh behind your back. You couldn't have known! Or could have you?

No one knows!

But I do know that this idea is fantastic, and you'll probably enjoy it a lot, and it probably won't catch your house on fire.

Active Ingredient Details:
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oxalic_acid

MSDS Data Sheet:
https://www.barkeepersfriend.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/SDS_BKF_Cleanser_Polish_6-12-15.pdf

**** PLEASE NOTE: If you have a different size container that looks similar to this (lots of cleansers come in this exact same container type - cardboard tube, metal top and bottom), please let me know the exact outside diameter of the container as measured by calipers, in mm. I would say try to round to the 0.5mm. And then, I will upload a special version with an I.D. that matches (tight for the bottom), and an I.D. that is 1mm larger, for the top. We can iterate until it's perfect, and I can even put your name right in the Summary and/or in the STL files themselves. Please don't forget to do the I Made One if you do, because it's cool to see people using the Things here!

Notes:

Frankly, printing these out with the flat-side on the bed and the walls facing up, the supports that Simplify 3D generated were extremely minimal. On the "top" version, it made a few squiggly lines at the four points of the compass, one or two layers deep. I know that some printers have different angles they can deal with, and it's possible your printer can handle the curves. Try it without supports if you're feeling lucky, and let me know if you were able to print one/both without them. Me, I print with them whenever I see a curve, just to be safe.

Easy Cleanup

If you print with supports, they should come away easily. No additional clean-up aside from the standard sanding, if you're feeling like finishing your part. With layer lines, the bottom print is very snug, while the top is perfectly loose. If you wanted an easy-to-remove bottom, and a really hard to take off top, just flip the two. We will absolutely make fun of you, free of charge!

Fusion 360 and Simplify3D

A tale as old as time! Fusion 360 for the design work, and Simplify3D for the slicing, dicing and automatic support generation. You really can't beat that combo!

description.text:
At first i wanted to print it as is and attach it to the hypercube, but i decided to go with a custom mount since i like it compact and did not want to attach something that potrudes from the side.
Also the base did not fit my MKS-TFT v1.2 so i had to break a little bit of the nut mount away. But i did not make an updated base - just keept it in mind. The original design by user dooit was nice and now since creating my "remix" i really enjoy using the display!

Thanks to user dooit for the great design!

Printer:

Hypercube

No

No

15%

Notes:

Print with front side of tilt-cover down. Print with flat side of tilt-mount down.

MATERIALS

1x 3D printed tilt-mount
1x 3D printed tilt-cover

4x M3x20mm Button Head screw ISO7380
4x M3 Hex nut
2x M3x10mm Button Head screw ISO7380
2x M5x10mm Button Head screw ISO7380
2x M5 T-Nut

1. Place the MKS TFT32 LCD display in between the cover and the base and use the M3x20mm button head screws and the hex nuts to close the case.

2. Then attach the tilt-mount to the 2020 extrusions with the M5 T-nuts and the M5 button head screws.

3. Use the M3x10mm button head screws to secure the display tilt-cover to the tilt-mount.

HINT
The display mount is designed so that the display hangs on the tilt-mount.

title: Prop drill guide for DLE30, RCGF30 and other RC gasoline motors

description.text:
This is a propeller drill guide for use with DLE30, RCGF30 and other RC gas motors that use 4mm bolts on a 26mm diameter pattern with a 10mm center shaft.

In addition to the printed parts a 3mm x 35mm (or 40mm) all thread bolt and 2 x 3mm nuts are required. This is designed to be used with a drill press, the 2 bases are used to prevent the prop from moving and to support it while being drilled and allow for clamping to the drill press table.
The 3mm bolt is inserted through the knob and tightened into place using one of the nuts, the other nut is placed into the guide itself. Prior to drilling a prop the drill bit should be run through each of the holes to clear and size them.
To use this guide clamp the propeller between the knurled nut and the guide, with the guide on the back side of the prop and align the guide holes to your preference. Clamp the base to the drill press table and place the nut side into the base, align and drill. When drilling, drill slowly and in stages to keep the hole clear.

The bit I use to drill the holes is an 11/64th, which is about 4.2mm and makes for a snug fit to the 4mm prop bolts.

I printed this in PLA, 0.25mm layers, 25% infill with 4 perimeters, the included gcode file should work well with Prussa I3 and clones.
